class Solution {
    /**
     * Solves the problem using dynamic programming.
     * dp_up[i]: maximum score of a valid alternating subsequence ending at index i, where nums[i] is greater than the previous element.
     * dp_down[i]: maximum score of a valid alternating subsequence ending at index i, where nums[i] is less than the previous element.
     * 
     * The constraints are:
     * 1. Subsequence indices i1 < i2 < ... < im < n.
     * 2. i_{t+1} - i_t >= k for all 1 <= t < m.
     * 3. The sequence is strictly alternating: nums[i1] < nums[i2] > nums[i3] < ... OR nums[i1] > nums[i2] < nums[i3] > ...
     * 
     * Base case: Any single element forms a valid sequence of score nums[i].
     * 
     * Transitions:
     * For dp_up[i] (ending with an ascent, i.e., previous < nums[i]):
     *   We look for a previous index j such that:
     *     a) j < i - k (distance constraint)
     *     b) nums[j] < nums[i] (ascent condition)
     *     c) The sequence ending at j must have ended with a descent (dp_down[j]) to maintain alternation.
     *   dp_up[i] = nums[i] + max(dp_down[j]) for all j < i - k and nums[j] < nums[i].
     *   If no such j exists, dp_up[i] = nums[i].
     * 
     * For dp_down[i] (ending with a descent, i.e., previous > nums[i]):
     *   We look for a previous index j such that:
     *     a) j < i - k (distance constraint)
     *     b) nums[j] > nums[i] (descent condition)
     *     c) The sequence ending at j must have ended with an ascent (dp_up[j]) to maintain alternation.
     *   dp_down[i] = nums[i] + max(dp_up[j]) for all j < i - k and nums[j] > nums[i].
     *   If no such j exists, dp_down[i] = nums[i].
     * 
     * Initialization: dp_up[i] = nums[i], dp_down[i] = nums[i] for all i.
     * 
     * The complexity of the naive DP is O(N^2), which is too slow given N=10^5.
     * We need an optimization.
     * 
     * The transitions involve finding the maximum of dp[j] over a range of j (j <= i-k) subject to a value constraint on nums[j].
     * This suggests using a data structure like a Segment Tree or Fenwick Tree (Binary Indexed Tree) on the values of nums.
     * Since values are up to 10^5, we can use coordinate compression or directly use the values as indices if they fit the data structure size.
     * Let V_max = 10^5.
     * 
     * We need two structures:
     * 1. `MaxDownBefore[v]`: Stores max(dp_down[j]) for all j <= i-k where nums[j] = v. (To compute dp_up[i])
     * 2. `MaxUpBefore[v]`: Stores max(dp_up[j]) for all j <= i-k where nums[j] = v. (To compute dp_down[i])
     * 
     * However, the index constraint j <= i-k is tricky because it changes with i. We cannot maintain a single global structure based on values that satisfies this moving window constraint efficiently.
     * 
     * We must iterate i from 0 to n-1. When calculating for i, we only care about j <= i-k.
     * 
     * Let's reconsider the structure. When we are at index i, we are looking at the set of indices J = {j | 0 <= j <= i-k}.
     * 
     * For dp_up[i] (nums[j] < nums[i], sequence ending at j is down):
     *   We need max(dp_down[j]) for j in J and nums[j] < nums[i].
     * 
     * For dp_down[i] (nums[j] > nums[i], sequence ending at j is up):
     *   We need max(dp_up[j]) for j in J and nums[j] > nums[i].
     * 
     * We can use two Fenwick Trees (or Segment Trees) indexed by value (1 to 10^5).
     * 
     * `BIT_down_up`: Stores max(dp_down[j]) at index nums[j] for indices j that are "ready" (i.e., j <= i-k).
     * `BIT_up_down`: Stores max(dp_up[j]) at index nums[j] for indices j that are "ready".
     * 
     * We process i from 0 to N-1.
     * 
